2026-05-29 | Count Valid Groupings of Digit String

	Question
Return total number of valid groupings.
	Key Insight
While forming groups:
		we only need to remember
		1. current position
		2. previous group digit sum
	This naturally leads to DP.
	Approach
1.	Define:
		solve(idx, prevSum)
		= number of valid ways
		  starting from idx
2.	From idx:
		keep extending current group
3.	Compute digit sum of current group
4.	If:
		currentSum >= prevSum
		then recursively process
		remaining string
5.	Memoize states
		(idx, prevSum)
6.	Base case:
		idx == n
		return 1
	Time Complexity
	O(n × maxPossibleSum × n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n × maxPossibleSum)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int dp[105][905];
    int solve(int idx,
              int prevSum,
              string &s){
        int n = s.size();
        if(idx == n)
            return 1;
        if(dp[idx][prevSum] != -1)
            return dp[idx][prevSum];
        int ans = 0;
        int currSum = 0;
        for(int j = idx; j < n; j++){
            currSum += (s[j] - '0');
            if(currSum >= prevSum){
                ans += solve(j + 1,
                             currSum,
                             s);
            }
        }
        return dp[idx][prevSum] = ans;
    }
    int TotalCount(string str) {
        memset(dp, -1, sizeof(dp));
        return solve(0, 0, str);
    }
};
	Key Insight
The difficult part is enforcing:
		group sums must be non-decreasing.
	So for every recursive state,
	we remember the previous group's sum
	and only allow future groups whose digit sum is at least that value. This converts the problem into a classic memoized DP.
